# Scenario
Can you chase a simulated adversary up the Pyramid of Pain until they finally back down? The challenge simulated a progressive threat detection exercise based on the Pyramid of Pain framework, requiring analysis of malware samples and application of increasingly impactful detection controls at each layer, from hash blocking up to behavioural TTPs.

# Tools Used
- TryHackMe Attack Box
- Malware Sandbox (in-platform)
- Hash Manager (in-platform)
- Firewall Manager (in-platform)
- DNS Filtering Tool (in-platform)
- Sigma Rule Builder (in-platform)
- Outgoing Connections Log (in-platform)
- Command Log (in-platform)

# What I Did

**Level 1 — Hash (Trivial)**
- Accessed the platform and opened the malicious email attachment in the malware sandbox for analysis.
- Sandbox returned the following hashes for sample1.exe:
  - MD5: cbda8ae000aa9cbe7c8b982bae006c2a
  - SHA1: 83d2791ca93e58688598485aa62597c0ebbf7610
  - SHA256: 9c550591a25c6228cb7d74d970d133d75c961ffed2ef7180144859cc09efca8c
- Submitted the SHA256 hash to the Hash Manager tool to block sample1.exe from executing.

**Level 2 — IP Address (Easy)**
- Ran the malware sandbox on sample2.exe.
- Analysis revealed an outbound connection to a malicious IP address: 154.35.10.113
- Added a deny egress rule in the Firewall Manager to block all outbound traffic to that IP:
  - Direction: Egress | Source: Any | Destination: 154.35.10.113 | Action: Deny

**Level 3 — Domain (Simple)**
- Ran the malware sandbox on sample3.exe.
- Analysis revealed a malicious domain used for C2 communication: emudyn.bresonicz.info
- Added a deny rule in the DNS Filtering tool to block resolution of the domain:
  - Category: Malware | Domain: emudyn.bresonicz.info | Action: Deny

**Level 4 — Host Artefacts (Annoying)**
- Ran the malware sandbox on sample4.exe.
- Analysis revealed registry modification activity targeting Windows Defender to disable real-time protection.
- Built a Sigma rule using the Sigma Rule Builder:
  - Log Source: Sysmon Event Logs
  - Detection Type: Registry Modifications
  - Registry Key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows Defender\Real-Time Protection
  - Registry Name: DisableRealtimeMonitoring
  - Value: 1
  - ATT&CK ID: Defense Evasion (TA0005)

**Level 5 — Tools (Challenging)**
- Ran the malware sandbox on sample5.exe and reviewed the outgoing connections log included in the attachment.
- Identified a beaconing pattern with consistent packet size and interval.
- Built a Sigma rule to detect this network behaviour:
  - Log Source: Sysmon Event Logs
  - Detection Type: Network Connections
  - Remote IP: Any
  - Remote Port: Any
  - Size (bytes): 97
  - Frequency (seconds): 1800
  - ATT&CK ID: Command and Control (TA0011)

**Level 6 — TTPs (Tough)**
- Reviewed the command log included in the final attachment to identify attacker behaviour at the TTP level.
- Identified a process creation event where cmd.exe was used to write data to a temp file as part of an exfiltration routine.
- Built a final Sigma rule targeting the specific command pattern:
  - Log Source: Sysmon Event Logs
  - Detection Type: Process Creations
  - Process Name: cmd.exe
  - CommandLine: Contains
  - String: %temp%\exfiltr8.log
  - ATT&CK ID: Exfiltration (TA0010)

