# Key Learning
The Pyramid of Pain demonstrates that not all indicators of compromise are equally costly to the adversary. Blocking a hash takes seconds for an attacker to bypass by recompiling, while detecting a TTP like a specific exfiltration command pattern forces them to fundamentally change their tooling and behaviour. Moving defences up the pyramid from hashes to IP addresses to domains to host artefacts to tools to TTPs makes detection increasingly painful for the attacker. Sigma rules provide a vendor-agnostic way to encode behavioural detections that translate across SIEM platforms.

# What I Would Flag in a Real SOC
- Hash-based blocking alone provides minimal protection, adversaries trivially recompile or repack malware to change file hashes while preserving functionality, hash IOCs should be the starting point not the endpoint of detection
- Outbound connections to hardcoded IP addresses are a strong indicator of unsophisticated C2, but IP blocking is equally easy to bypass by rotating infrastructure, network detections should focus on behavioural patterns rather than static indicators
- Disabling Windows Defender real-time monitoring via registry modification is a well-documented defense evasion technique (T1562.001) and should trigger an immediate high-priority alert in any production SIEM
- Beaconing traffic with a fixed packet size (97 bytes) and regular interval (every 30 minutes) is a classic C2 heartbeat pattern, network flow analysis tools should be configured to alert on statistically regular outbound traffic patterns
- Writing exfiltration data to %temp%\exfiltr8.log via cmd.exe is a behavioural TTP that survives tool changes, Sigma rules targeting this pattern will catch the adversary regardless of which binary they use to execute it
- TTP-level detections mapped to MITRE ATT&CK (TA0005, TA0011, TA0010) should be the primary focus of any mature SOC detection engineering programme as they are the hardest layer for adversaries to change
